# ConnectX-7 Direct-Connect Troubleshooting Guide

## For DGX Spark and other consumer/prosumer GPU systems with Mellanox ConnectX-7 NICs

This document covers every gotcha we hit bringing up a 4-node ring topology with direct-attach copper cables. If you're building a switchless GPU cluster with ConnectX-7 NICs, read this first. It will save you days.

---

## 1. Port Mapping: Which Physical Port Is Which?

**The Problem:** ConnectX-7 is a dual-port NIC. Each physical port exposes as a separate network interface. The naming convention does NOT make the mapping obvious, and getting it wrong means your cable appears "connected" (link UP, speed negotiated) but zero data flows.

**Interfaces you'll see:**

| Interface | Description |
|-----------|-------------|
| `enp1s0f0np0` / `rocep1s0f0` | Card 1, physical port 0 |
| `enp1s0f1np1` / `rocep1s0f1` | Card 1, physical port 1 |
| `enP2p1s0f0np0` / `roceP2p1s0f0` | Card 2, physical port 0 |
| `enP2p1s0f1np1` / `roceP2p1s0f1` | Card 2, physical port 1 |

**How to identify which port your cable is in:**

```bash
# Check which port has carrier (cable connected)
cat /sys/class/net/enP2p1s0f0np0/carrier  # 1 = cable present
cat /sys/class/net/enP2p1s0f1np1/carrier  # 1 = cable present

# Check physical port name
cat /sys/class/net/enP2p1s0f0np0/phys_port_name  # p0
cat /sys/class/net/enP2p1s0f1np1/phys_port_name  # p1

# WARNING: dev_port lies on Mellanox — both ports may report 0
cat /sys/class/net/enP2p1s0f0np0/dev_port  # Don't trust this
```

**The trap:** Link detection works on the wrong port. The NIC will negotiate 200Gbps and report `state UP` on a port that has no cable, because electrical signaling can leak between adjacent ports on the PCB. **Always verify with packet counters:**

```bash
# Send a ping, then check if TX increments on YOUR side
# and RX increments on the REMOTE side
cat /sys/class/net/<interface>/statistics/tx_packets
ping -c 1 -I <your_ip> <remote_ip>
cat /sys/class/net/<interface>/statistics/tx_packets
# If TX didn't change, you're on the wrong interface
```

