## 2. GID Table: RoCEv1 vs RoCEv2

**The Problem:** Each RDMA interface has a GID (Global Identifier) table with multiple entries. For IPv4-mapped addresses, you'll typically see the **same IP** at two different GID indices — one for RoCEv1 (IB-over-Ethernet framing) and one for RoCEv2 (UDP/IP encapsulation). Using the wrong one causes silent packet drops.

**Example GID table on ConnectX-7:**

```
GID[0]: fe80::... (link-local, RoCEv1)
GID[1]: fe80::... (link-local, RoCEv2)
GID[2]: ::ffff:192.168.103.2 (IPv4-mapped, RoCEv1)  ← WRONG for switchless
GID[3]: ::ffff:192.168.103.2 (IPv4-mapped, RoCEv2)  ← CORRECT
```

**Dump your GID table:**

```bash
for i in $(seq 0 7); do
    gid=$(cat /sys/class/infiniband/roceP2p1s0f1/ports/1/gids/$i 2>/dev/null)
    type=$(cat /sys/class/infiniband/roceP2p1s0f1/ports/1/gid_attrs/types/$i 2>/dev/null)
    [ -n "$gid" ] && echo "GID[$i]: $gid  type=$type"
done
```

**The fix:** Always scan for the **highest** IPv4-mapped GID index that matches your IP. On ConnectX-7, this is typically index 3 (RoCEv2). RoCEv1 works on switched networks but **fails on direct-connect** because there's no IB subnet manager to handle the v1 framing.

**Environment variable override:**

```bash
export MESH_RDMA_GID_INDEX=3
```

